<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="225" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after the Scythians, who were a nomadic tribe that dominated the steppes from the 
<number box="[1371,1383,548,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225" value="8.0">8</number>
th to approximately the 
<number box="[364,376,583,608]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225" value="3.0">3</number>
rd centuries BC. Scythian influence extended west to east from 
<collectingCountry box="[1106,1196,583,608]" name="Ukraine" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
to an area of Siberia just above 
<collectingCountry box="[272,384,620,645]" name="Mongolia" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
, including current territory of Tuva.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="225" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,523,655,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,655,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,434,655,680]" name="Russia" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Tuva).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,750,692,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,692,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="225">Ecology.</emphasis>
Inhabits sandy biotopes in steppe areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
